title: For Sale:   UNION SWITCH & SIGNAL / US&S ~ 1911A1 U.S. ARMY -- Nice Shape w/ Original Dulite Finish..
postcontent: Here's one of the harder to find WWII .45 automatics. This 1911A1 was manufactured by Union Switch & Signal in the autumn of 1943. Of the nearly 2-million 1911A1's manufactured during the Second World War, only 55,000 were manufactured by US&S. As manufacturers of 1911A1's go, only the fabled Singer is rarer. This pistol is in fine shape and appears to be all original. The frame is properly marked with the circled RCD acceptance found only on the US&S production. Both the frame and the slide are marked with the "P" proof which is correct for the later US&S pistols. The "P" proof on the slide is centered ahead of the rear sight...this is normally found on just slightly later production US&S pistols...but the internal & external wear patterns between slide, frame & barrel indicate these parts are original to one another. The other various parts are also correct for a US&S including the coarse checkered hammer, knurled mainspring housing, blued trigger, "concentric circle" barrel bushing, HS barrel, etc. The original Dulite blue finish is fully original and in very good overall condition with some normal expected handling & holster wear. There is thinning to the finish on the mainspring housing as well as a small amount of surface patina to the left front of the slide. There is a ding to the rear sight but no significant pitting anywhere. The frame's bullet ramp is milled in the white, as is correct for an original finish pistol. I'd grade the original finish at about 85-90% overall. The original Keyes Fibre grips are in very good shape although there is a small chip missing from the rear/bottom corner of the left panel. The mechanics are in perfect working order with everything working properly. The bore is less than ideal and while it shows strong rifling and is perfectly shootable, it exhibits the effects of corrosive ammo with light to moderate pitting throughout. This pistol comes with one original, good condition WWII M.S. Little Mfg. Co. contract magazine. This is a highly collectible 1911A1 and one of the most desirable of all WWII pistols.
